h, leaving roughly $12M attributable to API/other).\n*   **FY 2024:** AI Solutions & Infra grew by $254M. This was driven by a **$157M increase in X subscriptions** and a **$90M increase in data licensing** (accounting for $247M of the growth).\n*   **Q1 2026:** AI Solutions & Infra grew by $191M. This was driven by a **$177M increase in Grok and X subscriptions** and a **$12M increase in data licensing**.\n*   **API Revenue:** The text outlines the accounting policy for Grok API access (recognized ratably or as consumed) but **never quantifies** the API revenue in dollars or percentages.\n\n### 2. Inter-Segment Eliminations and Shared Revenue\n**There are no inter-segment revenue eliminations or shared revenue arrangements mentioned for the AI segment.** All AI revenues (Advertising, Subscriptions, Data Licensing, and API) are generated from external consumers and enterprise customers.\n\nHowever, the text does note an operational overlap regarding **internal launch capacity** between the segments:\n*   The **Space segment** allocates launch capacity internally to the Connectivity segment and expects to *"allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future"* (likely for AI data center/satellite infrastructure buildouts). \n*   To avoid the need for inter-segment revenue eliminations, the company explicitly states: *"Our Space segment revenue only reflects our customer launches and customer activities."* \n*   This means that when the Space segment launches payloads for the AI or Connectivity segments, it is treated as an internal cost/transfer rather than recognized as Space segment revenue. Therefore, no inter-segment revenue is recorded or eliminated on the consolidated income statement for these activities.',
